column37: A partially rotten 36-inch diameter tree was blown over and knocked down power lines.
column38: A cluster of thunderstorms developed ahead of an approaching cold front across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa during the pre-dawn hours of August 10th.  As a moist and highly unstable airmass fed into the system, the storms quickly intensified and began racing eastward  as a derecho across Iowa into northern Illinois along a pre-existing boundary.  While the greatest damage and highest wind speeds remained along and north of the I-80 corridor, a trailing boundary sank southward into central Illinois creating wind gusts of 60-75 mph.  As a result, widespread wind damage was reported along and north of a Macomb...to Springfield...to Paris line.

column38: A cluster of thunderstorms developed ahead of an approaching cold front across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa during the pre-dawn hours of August 10th.  As a moist and highly unstable airmass fed into the system, the storms quickly intensified and began racing eastward  as a derecho across Iowa into northern Illinois along a pre-existing boundary.  While the greatest damage and highest wind speeds remained along and north of the I-80 corridor, a trailing boundary sank southward into central Illinois creating wind gusts of 60-75 mph.  As a result, widespread wind damage was reported along and north of a Macomb...to Springfield...to Paris line.

After bringing extensive damage from extreme wind speeds in Iowa that morning, the damage transitioned across northern Illinois from widespread wind damage to narrow, brief and intense swaths associated with compact circulations within the thunderstorm line, some of which were associated with tornadoes.

column37: A corridor of significant wind damage occurred in Chicago, starting immediately east of Interstate 90/94 near Berteau and Kildare Avenues and continued northeast to near Montrose and Lawndale Avenues. One building suffered damage to a brick wall.  Damage occurred to the top of a brick business at the southeast corner of Pulaski Road and Elston Avenue.  Vehicles were damaged by the falling bricks.  Several roofs sustained damage northeast of Elston Avenue, just south of Montrose Avenue and a window was blown out of a house.  Two utility poles were damaged near Avers Avenue.  Three buildings along Montrose Avenue suffered significant roof damage just east of Hamlin Avenue.  Two buildings had west and south facing windows blown out near Montrose Avenue and Lawndale Avenue.  The damage in this corridor indicates peak winds of 95 mph.

column38: A cluster of thunderstorms developed ahead of an approaching cold front across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa during the pre-dawn hours of August 10th.  As a moist and highly unstable airmass fed into the system, the storms quickly intensified and began racing eastward  as a derecho across Iowa into northern Illinois along a pre-existing boundary.  While the greatest damage and highest wind speeds remained along and north of the I-80 corridor, a trailing boundary sank southward into central Illinois creating wind gusts of 60-75 mph.  As a result, widespread wind damage was reported along and north of a Macomb...to Springfield...to Paris line.

column37: A tornado with peak winds of 110 mph touched down in the Lincolnwood neighborhood of Chicago near the intersection of Lunt and Hamlin Avenues.  Tree damage occurred along most of the path of the tornado.  At least two city blocks were impassable due to fallen trees.  Numerous cars were totaled after trees fell on them.  Utility poles were leaning along Touhy Avenue, just east of St. Louis Avenue.  Significant tree damage including snapped trees, large trees uprooted and trees and tree limbs on vehicles, occurred between California Avenue and Rogers Phillip Park.  The most intense damage occurred approximately one mile west of Lake Michigan where widespread tree damage occurred including large trees 1 to 2 feet in diameter snapped and uprooted.  Minor roof damage also occurred in this area.  The tornado continued east to the Lake Michigan shore where it became a waterspout as it moved east of Fargo Beach Park.

column37: A corridor of significant straight line wind damage occurred from Harvey east to Calumet City.  Numerous trees were uprooted and snapped along this corridor.  Some roofs were damaged by falling trees; other roofs suffered minor shingle damage from the strong winds.  Some of the worst damage was in Harvey in an area between Sibley Boulevard to the north and 159th Street to the south.  Trees were snapped and uprooted and extensive damage occurred to utility poles and power lines, resulting in some portions of the power grid needing to be completely rebuilt.  Almost everyone in Harvey lost power.  An estimated 300 to 350 trees were blown down in Harvey.  Almost every road in Harvey was blocked by some amount of tree damage.  Significant tree damage was reported in forest preserve areas including in the Shabonna Woods Forest Preserve.  Damage was consistent with wind speeds up to 90 mph.||One day later, on August 11th, just after noon, a 59 year old man was walking in the 15000 block of Merrill Avenue in unincorporated Thornton Township near Calumet City.  He stepped on a downed power line that was live and collapsed in a grassy area where he died.
column38: During the late morning through the afternoon of Monday August 10th, a line of intense thunderstorms known as a derecho brought widespread severe wind damage across Iowa, northern Illinois and northern Indiana.||In north central and northeast Illinois alone, the severe winds of 60 to 100 mph downed or damaged tens of thousands of trees, as well as caused severe damage to homes, businesses, and infrastructure.  There were 10 injuries reported in north central and northeast Illinois within the NWS Chicago/Romeoville County Warning Area (CWA).  Local officials estimated that nearly one million customers lost power across northern Illinois at the height of the derecho and some people were without power for several days.  Damage was estimated to be in the hundreds of millions of dollars in north central and northeast Illinois, with several billions of dollars in damages across the entire Corn Belt region including significant damage to crops and agriculture infrastructure.  While much of the damage was due to straight line winds, there were also 14 tornadoes documented in north central and northeast Illinois.||The combination of high moisture, explosive instability and very strong atmospheric wind flow for mid-summer had developed quickly over the Corn Belt region on the morning of August 10th.  This resulted in a progressive, well-organized complex of storms for hundreds of miles and at times traveling nearly 70 mph.  After bringing extensive damage from extreme wind speeds in Iowa that morning, the damage transitioned across northern Illinois from widespread wind damage to narrow, brief and intense swaths associated with compact circulations within the thunderstorm line, some of which were associated with tornadoes.

column37: A 12-inch diameter tree branch was blown down.
column38: A cluster of thunderstorms developed ahead of an approaching cold front across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa during the pre-dawn hours of August 10th.  As a moist and highly unstable airmass fed into the system, the storms quickly intensified and began racing eastward  as a derecho across Iowa into northern Illinois along a pre-existing boundary.  While the greatest damage and highest wind speeds remained along and north of the I-80 corridor, a trailing boundary sank southward into central Illinois creating wind gusts of 60-75 mph.  As a result, widespread wind damage was reported along and north of a Macomb...to Springfield...to Paris line.

column37: Power was out, and five-inch tree limbs were down. A trained spotter estimated wind gusts near 75 mph.
column38: A bow-shaped line of severe thunderstorms moved southeast across southern Illinois, producing scattered areas of wind damage. The storms moved through a pool of moderate to strong instability, where mixed-layer cape ranged from 3000 to 3500 J/kg. The storms weakened later in the evening as they moved southward into an area of weaker deep-layer winds. The line of storms originated over the central Plains and upper Mississippi Valley earlier in the day. Despite moving far from the disturbance that triggered them, the storms remained intense as they fed off strong instability.

The storms weakened later in the evening as they moved southward into an area of weaker deep-layer winds. The line of storms originated over the central Plains and upper Mississippi Valley earlier in the day. Despite moving far from the disturbance that triggered them, the storms remained intense as they fed off strong instability.

column38: Showers and thunderstorms increased in coverage and intensity through the day as daytime heating destabilized the atmosphere. The slow-moving storms occurred near a stalled frontal boundary that extended from northeast Missouri across southern Illinois to central Kentucky. Precipitable water values were near two inches. As a result, rainfall rates in thunderstorms were as much as two to three inches per hour.

column37: Multiple roadways were flooded and impassable, including Route 148 in Christopher. Water was over Route 14 in Christopher. Water was encroaching on several residences.
column38: Scattered thunderstorms produced very heavy rain across the lower Ohio Valley. The storms occurred in a moist and unstable air mass ahead of a slow-moving 500 mb disturbance over south central Illinois. The slow-moving storms initiated along a weak|low level convergence axis stretching from east central Missouri into southern Illinois and northwestern Kentucky. Precipitable water values across the region ranged from 1.6 to 2.0 inches, supporting locally heavy rainfall rates near two inches per hour.

column37: Up to four inches of rain fell in a two hour period on already saturated soils. This caused flash flooding in northwestern portions of Randolph County. Numerous roads were flooded including Illinois Route 3 near Ruma.
column38: An upper level disturbance provided large scale ascent and plenty of moisture, producing storms that were efficient rain producers. Up to four inches of rain fell onto already saturated soils causing isolated flash flooding.

In the early morning of September 10th, a 20 year old male was walking with two friends near Oak Street Beach.  He decided to jump into Lake Michigan and needed to be rescued by the Chicago Police Marine unit.  He was taken to a hospital in critical condition and died a few hours later.  Waves were around 5 feet.  In the early afternoon of September 11th, a woman in her 20s was pulled from Lake Michigan near 87th Street.  She was taken to a hospital in critical condition and later died.  Waves were around 4 feet.

Dry and windy conditions were responsible for several fires, including a 200-acre wildfire on reclaimed strip mine property about three miles south of Equality. Volunteer firefighters from across Gallatin, Saline, and Hardin Counties were assisted by federal fire crews from the Shawnee National Forest.

Dry and windy conditions created dangerous fire conditions on October 14th.  A large wildfire started in a field about 6 miles west of Danforth during the afternoon of October 14th.  The fire quickly spread with strong southerly winds gusting to 50 mph along with relative humidity levels as low as 20 percent.  Multiple fire departments responded and it wasn't until farmers arrived to start making fire breaks that the fire was brought under control and eventually put out, over 5 hours after it started.  The cause of the fire was not known.  No damage to structures was reported though approximately 40 acres of grain was lost.  The size of the fire was estimated around 580 acres, using high resolution satellite imagery.

column37: Reports of tree limbs and power lines down throughout the county. Time estimated using radar.
column38: A strong and quick moving cold front made its way through the Midwest. The environment ahead of the cold front was unseasonably warm, with temperatures in the upper 60s and readings in the 40s not far behind the front. This led to strong baroclinicity along the front, and subsequent convection with just the right amount of instability. This is considered a high shear low CAPE (HSLC) event, where organized severe thunderstorms are favored in this environment. Potential hazards are damaging winds, large hail, and tornadoes. Six tornadoes were confirmed and several wind reports were received (ranging between 50-60 mph, with a few gusts over 60 mph). Damage reports ranged from structural damage to tree damage. Many residents were left without power in parts of northwestern IL, leading to some schools canceling classes on the 11th. Besides the strong winds, a few severe hail reports were received.||In addition, heavy rain occurred with some of the stronger storms, with rainfall totals over an inch. For how dry it has been, flash flooding was not much of a concern. While the environment was very moist and favorable for heavy rainfall, the fast storm motions led to little accumulation through much of our forecast area.

Besides the strong winds, a few severe hail reports were received.||In addition, heavy rain occurred with some of the stronger storms, with rainfall totals over an inch. For how dry it has been, flash flooding was not much of a concern. While the environment was very moist and favorable for heavy rainfall, the fast storm motions led to little accumulation through much of our forecast area.

column38: A cold front interacting with an unseasonably warm and humid airmass triggered scattered strong to severe thunderstorms across the Illinois River Valley during the afternoon of November 10th.  The storms produced wind gusts of 50 to 70 mph and caused periodic damage...especially in Elmwood and Kickapoo in Peoria County where a couple roofs were blown off.

column37: A tornado with peak winds of 80 mph touched down near Route 23 northwest of the town of Somonauk and traveled northeast mainly through farm fields.  A grain silo was damaged near the intersection of Somonauk and Bastian Roads, and damage to trees and powerlines was observed along the path of the tornado.  The tornado appeared to end near Route 30 just southeast of Hinckley.  The path of this tornado was determined based on input from spotters, emergency management and using radar data.

High winds gusting to 69 mph produced scattered wind damage in the late morning and afternoon of November 15th.  In Cook County, Midway Airport (MDW) measured a peak wind gust to 69 mph.  A nearby cooperative observer also measured a peak wind gust to 69 mph.  A large tree limb fell in the 3000 block of East Cheltenham Place, striking a gas meter and multiple cars.  A traffic signal was blown down on Archer Avenue in Bridgeport.  A medium to large tree was blown down across Larabee Street.  In Oak Lawn, a portion of an apartment building roof was blown off.  In Will County, a semi truck was overturned on southbound Interstate 57 between exit 327 and exit 322.  In Kankakee County, a tree approximately one and a half feet in diameter was blown down south of Kankakee.  In Kane County, Sugar Grove Airport (ARR) measured a peak wind gust to 59 mph.

column38: An early season winter storm lead to widespread snowfall throughout the area, with totals of 2 to 6 inches across far northwest Illinois. Precipitation began as rain, with warm, moist air in place across the region. The rain changed over to snow during the evening hours along and Highway 20 corridor.  By 6:00am on the 12th, the snow had spread as far south as Interstate 80.The snow was heavy at times, especially near the area where rain was changing to snow. Key impacts: transportation delays and traffic accidents.

Strong south winds occurred ahead of a cold front as it sliced eastward across Missouri. Gusts over 40 mph were recorded in the Mississippi River delta, from Cairo up to East Cape Girardeau and Grand Tower. The highest measured gust was 55 mph at a mesonet site just southeast of Grand Tower in Jackson County. The peak gust at the Carbondale airport was 39 mph.

column38: A potent winter storm produced widespread heavy snow, along with freezing rain and sleet, across the region in the afternoon and through the evening of the 29th into the early morning hours of the 30th. 8 to 12 inches of snow fell in the heaviest band between Interstate 80 and U.S. Highway 20. The highest freezing rain accumulations occurred from near Oquawka to Kewanee IL, where 0.2 to 0.3 inches of glaze ice was reported. Key impacts: transportation delays and traffic accidents, along with some isolated power outages.

A winter storm moved across northern Illinois from the afternoon of December 29th through the early morning of December 30th.  Moderate to heavy snow spread across northern Illinois by late afternoon with snow quickly accumulating on roads making for a slow afternoon commute.  The heaviest snow occurred across northwest Illinois.  The highest snowfall totals included 9.5 inches in Lake Summerset; 8.1 inches in Winnebago; 6.2 inches at the Rockford Airport, 6.0 inches near Brookville and 6.0 inches near Dixon.  Snowfall amounts were generally in the 3 to 5 inch range across the rest of northern Illinois.  The snow transitioned to freezing rain across many areas where one to two tenths of ice accumulated by the morning of December 30th.
